column17: No Rain it just hot and crowded
No rain, no clouds, Nope crowded just a few peope waiting for the train and the Platform was just so hot

No rain, clear skies.
The WTC Cortlandt 1 train station was surprisingly cool but not cold. If you go near the air conditioning units built into the wall, you’ll feel cold air blowing into the station. I noticed that a lot of people were standing by the wall just to cool down — it’s become a little oasis from the heat.

No rain, clear skies.
The platform was moderately crowded — not packed, but definitely busy. It was hot in the station, especially when two trains stopped at the same time at Bowling Green. The heat really built up in that moment.

No rain, clear skies.
There were only a few people on the platform at first. But when I reached the turnstiles, it was packed — lots of people waiting to catch the 1 or R train. Most of them were coming from the Staten Island Ferry. There was a long line of us trying to pay the fare, and I was one of them.

It started getting hot, especially when the train didn’t come right away. Sometimes it’s delayed, but today it was mostly on time. At the South Ferry station, there’s some cool air blowing from the top of the station, but it’s not strong enough to cool the whole place down. When the train arrives on schedule, the crowd clears out a bit. But if it's late, the heat and crowd build up fast — it gets really uncomfortable.
A very crowded station, but with stable conditions
Very empty station
This station has vents that span about half the platform leading to street level i believe this has something to do with the significantly lower humidity in the station.

There was no rain, but the sky was overcast. The 14th Street–Union Square (4 train) station was very crowded, with many people waiting on the platform. Although the station has large ceiling fans, it felt like the fans were circulating hot air rather than providing any real cooling. The fan placement and ventilation system do not seem effective in keeping the station cool.

There was no rain or overcast clouds. The Grand Central–42nd Street station for the 4, 5, and 6 trains was extremely hot. Although there were fans on the platform, they were not enough to cool down the area—it still felt very hot. The platform was moderately crowded and felt small, especially considering it serves three train lines. However, near the turnstiles, inside the Grand Central Terminal building, it was noticeably cooler. That seemed to be the only area with proper ventilation and cooling.

There was no rain, just overcast clouds. The 7 train platform at Grand Central was the coolest area so far compared to the 4, 5, 6 platforms. From what I noticed, this area only has the 7 train and fewer people. They also have ceiling fans, which help a little, but not that much.

column17: There was no rain, just overcast skies. The temperature inside the 7 train station at 34th Street–Hudson Yards was 83.1°F, with a humidity level of 51.7%. It felt cool compared to other stations. There were a lot of vents, which helped circulate cool air throughout the station. The platform was large and not very crowded. So far, this has been the coolest station I’ve visited, and it’s also very deep underground.

column17: At the time, it was drizzling outside. It felt more like light drops, not real rain, with overcast clouds. The platform was kind of crowded, and there were no fans or anything to help cool the station.

It was drizzling earlier, but the rain stopped. There were overcast clouds. The station itself felt cool, even though it wasn’t very busy. There were some of cool air inside the station.

Notes: Professor Bah, I think you made a mistake. You listed the Q and F trains for 72 St, 86 St, and 96 St, but the F train does not stop at those stations. The F train stops at Lexington Av/63 St, which is its last stop in Manhattan before continuing to Queens. The Q train, on the other hand, stays entirely in Manhattan, and its last stop is 96 St.

When I came out of the 86 St station, it was cloudy and looked like it was going to rain, but there was no rain at the time. The station itself felt cool, around 83.7°F. Maybe it wasn’t as hot anymore compared to an hour earlier.

When I came out of the station, it had just started to rain, but it wasn’t too bad—just normal rain with cloudy weather. The station gets cooler when it’s raining or cloudy, which is a good thing for the riders.
